(161, 1, '2011-11-11 20:53:14', '2011-11-11 20:53:14', 'Bill Hodapp, St. Regis Park Public Safety Officer, has offered the following information that will be useful to keep you and your families safe year round.  Contact him at 671-9469 or at bekainc@hotmail.com with any questions or comments.\r\n\r\n<strong>HOME SECURITY</strong>\r\n\r\nKeep your exterior lights on at night, garage doors closed, cars locked and place valuables (bikes, lawn equipment, etc) out of visible sight. You also want to secure all windows and doors when not at home and consider the installation of a home security system.\r\n\r\nIf you have any type of criminal activity, please report it to LMPD. The more information the police have, the more resources they will provide to our neighborhood.\r\n\r\nIf you have a streetlight that needs repaired, contact me or LG&amp;E.\r\n<strong>\r\nBLOCK WATCH</strong>\r\n\r\nI am in the process of re-establishing the Block Watch program and need volunteers. Please send an e-mail to bekainc@hotmail.com if you have an interest in helping.\r\n\r\n<strong>DISASTER PLAN</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Council is in the process of creating a disaster plan. The plan will require zone captains that will report to the Public Safety Officer. We plan to have a list of people that can help coordinate clearing of roads, driveways, and offer assistance to the elderly that may require uninterrupted service for oxygen use and any other activities that will keep our City safe. We would also like to identify neighbors that are certified in first aid and CPR.\r\n\r\n<strong>EVACUATION PLAN</strong>\r\n\r\nDevelop a fire evacuation plan for your family and practice the drill. Know where to meet and don’t re-enter the home to find pets or get personal items.\r\n\r\n<strong>SMOKE DETECTORS</strong>\r\n\r\nWhere you place smoke detectors depends on the size and layout of your home, and where people sleep in your home. Since the primary job of a smoke detector is to awaken sleeping persons and warn them of urgent danger, put a detector in each sleeping room and place additional detector(s) in the hallway or area by the bedrooms within five feet of the door to these rooms. In a house where the bedrooms are upstairs, one additional detector should be near the top of the stairs to the bedroom area.\r\n\r\nDon''t put detectors within six inches of where walls and ceilings meet, or near heating and cooling ducts. Detectors located in these areas may not receive the flow of smoke required to activate the alarm. You may want to also install detectors in your laundry room and garage.\r\n\r\nI would recommend a 10 year tamperproof detector which can be found at local retail stores.\r\n\r\n<strong>FIRE EXTINGUISHERS</strong>\r\n\r\nI would recommend having a 5# ABC rated extinguisher in your kitchen, laundry room and garage. I have found that the on-line price is about $26 but you may find a less expensive extinguisher at a local retail store and save on shipping. Please read the directions and know how to use the extinguisher. You may also qualify for a reduction in your homeowners insurance.\r\n\r\n<strong>CARBON MONOXIDE (CO) MONTIORS</strong>\r\n\r\nCO is the number one cause of poisoning death in America. It is an odorless, invisible, and extremely dangerous gas, which can be given off by the most common appliances in your home or even a car in an attached garage. You cannot see or smell carbon monoxide, but at high levels it can kill a person in minutes. Carbon monoxide (CO) is produced whenever any fuel such as gas, oil, kerosene, wood, or charcoal is burned. When appliances that burn fuel are maintained and properly used, the amount of CO produced is usually not hazardous. However, if appliances are not working properly or are used incorrectly, dangerous levels of CO can result. Hundreds of people die accidentally every year from CO poisoning caused by malfunctioning or improperly used fuel-burning appliances. Even more die from CO produced by idling cars.\r\nAgain, CO monitors can be found at your local retail stores and you must follow the manufacturer’s instructions.\r\n\r\n<strong>ESCAPE LADDERS</strong>\r\n\r\nSomeone in the U.S. dies in a home fire every three hours, according to the The National Fire Protection Association, which recommends one ladder in every occupied room on floors above the main level. A fire escape Ladder provides a means of escape from a fire if you live in a two or three story home. It stores easily under the bed or near a window, and is quick and easy to use.\r\n\r\n<strong>RADON</strong>\r\n\r\nThe U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) and the Surgeon General''s Office have estimated that as many as 20,000 lung cancer deaths are caused each year by radon. Radon is the second leading cause of lung cancer. Radon-induced lung cancer costs the United States over $2 billion dollars per year in both direct and indirect health care costs. (Based on National Cancer Institute statistics of 14,400 annual radon lung cancer deaths - Oster, Colditz &amp; Kelley, 1984)\r\n\r\nYou can search the web or go to a local hardware store to find an inexpensive test kit that will allow you to measure the radon levels in your home.', 'Handy Safety Measures', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '159-revision-2', '', '', '2011-11-11 20:53:14', '2011-11-11 20:53:14', '', 159, 'http://www.stregispark.net/index.php/2011/11/11/159-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(163, 1, '2011-10-14 14:06:25', '2011-10-14 14:06:25', '<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-141" title="propertytaxes" src="http://www.stregispark.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/propertytaxes.gif" alt="" width="190" height="100" /><strong>Send tax payments to:</strong>\r\nCity of St. Regis Park, 3917 Solutions Center, Chicago, IL 60677-3009\r\n\r\nThe City''s activities are funded largely by an annual property tax levy. The property taxes are levied on the real property values of each home as supplied by the Jefferson County Property Valuation Administrator (PVA). St. Regis Park property tax bills are  mailed out in July. The payments are due October 31st. Penalties and interest applies to late payments of the bill. Please check the property tax bill you receive for any penalties which may apply. Bills are not sent to mortgage companies by the City. It is the property owners responsibility to do this. Tax bills that remain unpaid on November 1 are delinquent. Liens are filed for tax bills that remain unpaid on January 1. The tax bill is generally paid out of an escrow account . Please check with your mortgage company if you have any question about a property tax escrow arrangement. Homestead or Disability exemptions are allowed residents of retirement age and those who are handicapped. If you believe you qualify for Homestead Exemption or Disability Exemption, please contact the Jefferson County Property Valuation Administration for details.\r\n\r\n<strong>MULTIPLE PAYMENT OF TAXES</strong>\r\nIf the City receives more than one payment of City taxes, the extra payment is remitted to the property owner – not the mortgage company. The City makes all multiple payment refunds after the payment deadline of October 31.\r\nThe Jefferson County Property Valuation Administrator reassesses all real estate properties throughout Jefferson County approximately every two years.The City of St. Regis Park bases its property tax  on the Jefferson County property assessments. If you take exception to the assessed value of your property and want to appeal it, you must contact the Jefferson County Property Valuation Administrator. The telephone number for the Jefferson County Property Valuation Administrator is included with the list of telephone numbers contained in this brochure.', 'Taxes', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '50-revision-6', '', '', '2011-10-14 14:06:25', '2011-10-14 14:06:25', '', 50, 'http://www.stregispark.net/index.php/2011/10/14/50-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
